occurrences.line_text: That euer troden was of footings trace.
Where, as he to and fro by chaunce did trace,
And by which way they towards it should trace.
To tread an endlesse trace, withouten guyde,
To find him out, yet still I forward trace.
Not wont on foote with heauy armes to trace,
Had vow'd vnto the victor, him to trace
For Coridon could daunce, and trimly trace.
Still in a knot, vnto her heeles downe traced,
How all the way the Prince on footpace traced,
But that fourth Mayd, which there amidst the[m] traced,
Traceth his ground, and round about doth beat,
Tracing and trauersing, now here, now there;
Which when by tract they hunted had throughout,
In which the tract of peoples footing was,
Or by what meanes may I his footing tract?
Tract of his foot: then dead through great affright
Yet tract of liuing creatures none they found,
By tract of bloud, which she had freshly seene,
For thy, the bloudy tract they follow fast,
Had borne him, or his tract she mote detect:
If any tract of him or tydings they mote trace.
Farre vnder ground from tract of liuing went,
But tract of time, that all things doth decay,
He could no path nor tract of foot descry,
Well did he tract his steps, as he did ryde,
That she in tract of time accompted was his owne.
Him follow'd, by the tract of his outragious spoile.
Hath tracted forth some saluage beastes trade;
With streames of bloud; which tracting by the traile,
Accursed vsurie was all his trade,
Hath tracted forth some saluage beastes trade;
Finding in it fit ports for fishers trade,
There those fiue sisters had continuall trade,
Where so loose life, and so vngentle trade
Or ply him selfe to any honest trade,
To win faire Leda to his louely trade:
His name was Care; a blacksmith by his trade,
Whose cursed vsage and vngodly trade
Aswell which in the mightie Ocean trade,
Thereto adde art, euen womens witty trade,
Shut vp her hauen, mard her marchants trade,
Them selues to any trade, as for to driue
Was hunting in the woods (as was his trade)
But through traduction was eftsoones deriued,
And by such trafficke after gaines to hunt,
Tell on (quoth she) the wofull Tragedie,
The end of their sad Tragedie vptyde,
The sad spectatour of my Tragedie;
In middest of their mournfull Tragedy,
But to declare the mournfull Tragedyes,
Yclad in costly garments, fit for tragicke Stage.
And tragicke Inoes sonne, the which became
Great ruth through her misfortunes tragicke stowre;
To stirre vp strife, and many a Tragicke stowre,
Slaying Traherne, and hauing ouercome
With streames of bloud; which tracting by the traile,
That hast with knightlesse guile and trecherous train
There all my dayes he traind me vp in vertuous lore.
Traind vp in feats of armes and knightlinesse;
And both in armes well traind and throughly tride.
Lept fierce vpon his shield, and her huge traine
God helpe the man so wrapt in Errours endlesse traine.
Such one was Lecherie, the third of all this traine.
Of proud Lucifer', as one of the traine:
That with their sturre they troubled all the traine;
As to descry the crafty cunning traine,
No false enchauntment, nor deceiptfull traine
And scourging th'emptie ayre with his long traine,
O neuer Sir desire to try his guilefull traine.
Then gan he tosse aloft his stretched traine,
The whiles that hoarie king, with all his traine,
In vertuous lore to traine his tender youth,
Below her ham her weed were somewhat traine,
She forth issewed with a goodly traine
The traine whereof loose far behind her strayd,
In the meane time through that false Ladies traine,
Seeking to match the chaste with th'vnchaste Ladies traine.
And marshalling the euill ordered traine,
The noble Thamis, with all his goodly traine,
And both behind vpheld her spredding traine;
That all the sea disturbed with their traine,
How he mis-led the simple peoples traine,
His horse purloyned was by subtill traine:
Of treason, or some guilefull traine did weaue,
In traytrous traine, or had vnwares opprest:
She was preserued from their traytrous traine.
Which dreadfull sight, when all her warlike traine
To lay his spoiles before his lemans traine:
Whether ye list him traine in cheualry,
Ne yet entrap in treasons subtill traine.
What and from whence she was, and by what traine
T'aduize him better, then by such a traine
Whether it were the traine of beauties Queene,
I haue beene trained vp in warlike stowre,
And trained vp in true feminitee:
Hauing therein bene trained many a yeare,
The subtill traines of Archimago old;
With cunning traines him to entrap vnwares.
Duessaes traines and Malecastaes
For through his traines he her intrapped hath,
The traines of wit, in wickednesse woxe bold,
But that he seekes by traytrous traines to spill
Ere that I in her guilefull traines was well expert.
Who then would thinke, that by his subtile trains
My name with guile and traiterous intent;
Light-shonning theft, and traiterous intent,
False traitour miscreant, thou broken hast
False traitour squire, false squire, of falsest knight,
In breaded tramels, that no looser heares
Her golden locks, that were in tramels gay
And trample th'earth, the whiles they may respire;
Who vnder him did trample as the aire,
And trampled downe in dust his thoughts disdained scorne.
That in his chauffe he digs the trampled ground,
And trampling the fine element, would fiercely rampe.
Who taught his trampling steed with equall steps to tread.
Whose trampling feet vpon the hollow lay
A trampling steede, that with his neighing fast
That hauing cast him in a foolish trance,
And trouble dying soules tranquilitee.
Who ioyd his dayes in great tranquillity,
Ne euer rests he in tranquillity,
Whenas the God to golden hew him selfe transfard.
And Cambell it to Triamond transferd;
All sodainely she saw transfigured
And doth transfixe the soule with deathes eternall dart.
As if her hart with sorrow had transfixed beene.
Him so transfixed she before her bore
Transfixed with the speare, downe tombled ded
Quite through transfixed with a deadly dart,
Seeming transfixed with a cruell dart,
It had himselfe transfixed, or his horse,
The bold Semiramis, whose sides transfixt
Hath thus transformd, and plast in open plaines,
Into an Oxe he was transform'd of yore:
The wretched payre transform'd to treen mould;
Transformd her to a stone from stedfast virgins state.
Transform'd to fish, for their bold surquedry,
To which sad louers were transformd of yore;
Whom then she does transforme to mo[n]strous hewes,
To dreadfull shapes he did himselfe transforme,
Then to a bush himselfe he did transforme,
And so transformed from his former skill,
Whom this Enchauntresse hath transformed thus,
Transformed oft, and chaunged diuerslie:
Are now transformed into hardest stone:
There they doe say, that she transformed was
If euer he transgrest the fatall Stygian lawes.
For other vses, then they them translated;
Men into stones therewith he could transmew,
Him to a dainty flowre she did transmew,
Soone into other fits he was transmewed,
That to a Centaure did him selfe transmoue.
And that she did transport the same by sea,
Or that my fortunes might transposed bee
To decke his herce, and trap his tomb-blacke steed.
And in the same are many trap fals pight,
Should meete, a trap was letten downe to fall
Did cast for to allure, into her trap to fall.
By a false trap was let adowne to fall
Into her trap vnto their owne decay:
With tinsell trappings, wouen like a waue,
And all her steed with tinsell trappings shone,
But he at first or last was trapt in womens snare.
Thus long they trast, and trauerst to and fro,
He had not trauaild long, when on the way
Ere long he came, where Vna traueild slow,
Long with her traueild, till at last they see
Great troupes of people traueild thitherward
They traueild had, when as they farre espide
As he had traueild many a sommers day,
They sadly traueild thus, vntill they came
So as they traueild, lo they gan espy
I lately traueild, that vnwares I strayd
In this faire wize they traueild long yfere,
For still he traueild through wide wastfull ground,
Who ere he thence had traueild many a mile,
Long time they thus together traueiled,
Long she thus traueiled through deserts wyde,
All bare through peoples feet, which thither traueiled.
So long they traueiled with litle ease,
Thus long they three together traueiled,
That neuer leads the traueiler astray,
Espye a traueiler with feet surbet,
The wearie Traueiler, wandring that way,
But he, not like a wearie traueilere,
By which he freed the Traueilers high way,
That by the wearie way were traueiling,
Till that Latona traueiling that way,
Als Vna earnd her traueill to renew.
There where through weary trauel she lay sleeping sou[n]d.
They trauel'd long, that now for wearinesse,
There as he traueld by the way, he met
So forth they traueld an vneuen payre,
So both together traueld, till they met
Had traueld still on foot in heauie armes,
In trauell to and froe: a little wyde
His sandales were with toilesome trauell torne,
To see two knights in trauell on my way
Which in his trauell him befallen had,
After his trauell long, and labours manifold.
Faire Sir, if euer there ye trauell, shonne
And thought his labour lost and trauell vaine,
But neither toyle nor trauell might her backe recoyle.
For here the end of all our trauell is:
Because of trauell long, a nigher way,
To trauell, goe to see that dreadfull place:
But there doe toyle and trauell day and night,
Rich strond to trauell, whereas he did wonne,
Where wearie of long trauell, downe to rest
He hauing through incessant trauell spent
To weet, that I my trauell should resume,
The Palfrey, whereon she did trauell, slew,
Agreed to trauell, and their fortunes try.
After so long a trauell, which them both did tire.
Him selfe, whose minde did trauell as with chylde,
Hath me much sorrow and much trauell cost;
Long were to tell the trauell and long toile,
By which as they did trauell on a day,
Weary of toile and trauell of that day,
After long trauell of full twenty yeares,
For so great trauell, as you doe sustaine:
My tedious trauell doe forget thereby;
And now he was in trauell on his way,
Through all my weary trauell I haue had:
Did sleepe all night through weary trauell of his quest.
With wearie trauell and vncertaine toile,
To passe the tedious trauell of the way;
Endure to trauell, nor one foote to frame:
Wearie of trauell in his former fight,
Of her long trauell and turmoyling paine;
Where being tyrde with trauell, and opprest
Great trauell hath the gentle Calidore
Long way he trauelled, before he heard of ought.
Long so they trauelled through wastefull wayes,
Long they thus trauelled in friendly wise,
And whither now he trauelled so fast:
So long she trauelled, till at length she came
To passe that way, as forth he trauelled;
By great aduenture trauelled that way;
So as they trauelled, the drouping night
We trauelled, both wearie of the way
So as he trauelled vppon the way,
Sir Calidore thence trauelled not long,
As when a wearie traueller that strayes
Of the poore traueller, that went astray,
A traueller vnwonted to such way:
No lesse, then rockes, (as trauellers informe,)
T'allure weake trauellers, whom gotten they did kill.
That trauellers to him seemd to entize;
All trauellers; therefore aduise ye well,
All trauellers tormented are with paine:
Is he, that doth to trauellers such harmes?
Whom bold Cymochles trauelling to find,
She trauelling with Guyon by the way,
So trauelling, he chaunst far off to heed
In trauelling on foote so long a space,
Who trauels by the wearie wandring way,
That forced him his ground to trauerse wide,
Tracing and trauersing, now here, now there;
Thus long they trac'd, and trauerst to and fro,
Thus long they trast, and trauerst to and fro,
Thus long they trac'd and trauerst to and fro,
He answered nought, but in a traunce still lay,
Where Guyon lay in traunce, when suddenly
By this Sir Guyon from his traunce awakt,
Faire Crysogone in slombry traunce whilere:
A trayle of yuie in his natiue hew:
Trayled with ribbands diuersly distraught
Which had them traynd in all ciuilitee,
Artegall trayn'd in Iustice lore
A dreadfull Dragon with an hideous trayne,
Of comely seruices, or courtly trayne?
And with him led to sea an youthly trayne,
Which them to warlike discipline did trayne,
He trayned was, till ryper yeares he raught,
He had not trayned bene in cheualree.
So was she trayned vp from time to time,
Thus she him trayned, and thus she him taught,
In which he had bene trayned many a day,
Haue trayned bene with many noble feres
As if he long had to his heasts bene trayned.
Or to allure such fondlings, whom she trayned
By traynes into new troubles to haue tost:
Yet first he cast by treatie, and by traynes,
And all her traynes, and all her treasons forth did lay.
And traynes hauing surpriz'd, he fouly did to die.
The wicked driftes of trayterous desynes,
And either both them drownes, or trayterously slaies.
But also trayterously did wound her weary Knight.
Thou recreant false traytor, that with lone
False traytor Knight, (sayd she) no Knight at all,
Art thou he, traytor, that with treason vile,
Is there possessed of the traytour vile,
Sith that false Traytour did my honour reaue?
False traytour certes (said the Faerie knight)
Traytour what hast thou doen? how euer may
Bidding him turne againe, false traytour knight,
The traytour Turpin with that other knight,
In traytrous traine, or had vnwares opprest:
She was preserued from their traytrous traine.
But that he seekes by traytrous traines to spill
As for Grandtorto, him with treacherie
Then to entrap him by false treacherie:
By treacherous deceipt did me depriue;
But voide of vile and treacherous intent,
And many brought to shame by treason treacherous.
Like treacherous, like full of fraud and guile,
But him Allectus treacherously slew,
Least any should betray his Lady treacherously.
To keepe a nightly watch, for dread of treachery.
In which the king was by a Treachetour
Abide ye caytiue treachetours vntrew,
No knight, but treachour full of false despight
Where may that treachour then (said he) be found,
The whiles to me the treachour did remoue
Till I that treachours art haue heard and tride;
And vnderneath his filthy feet did tread
Where neuer foot of liuing wight did tread,
And with his winged heeles did tread the wind,
Whereon thy innocent feet doe euer tread,
Be wonne their rightfull causes downe to tread:
Ne weene my right with strength adowne to tread,
Who taught his trampling steed with equall steps to tread.
She taught to tread, when she her selfe would grace,
For he despysd to tread in dew degree,
And ouerrun to tread them to the ground.
The verdant grasse, as he thereon did tread;
And Penda, seeking him adowne to tread,
Shall tread adowne, and do him fowly dye,
In their auenge, tread downe the victours surquedry.
I tread in dust thee and thy money both,
Vnworthy wretch to tread vpon the ground,
And kist the ground on which her sole did tread,
I count as naught, and tread downe vnder feet,
The waters depth, and doth their bottome tread;
Then gan he make him tread his steps anew,
Aboue the brincke, to tread vpon the land,
To tread an endlesse trace, withouten guyde,
To driue you so on foot vnfit to tread,
That euery foote did tremble, which did tread,
Which tosseth states, and vnder foot doth tread
And treading vnder foote her honest name:
His nimble feet, as treading still on thorne:
Or flings aloft, or treads downe in the flore,
Treads downe and ouerthrowes. Now had the Carle
She them besought, during their quiet treague,
And shamefull treason, who through guile hath slayn
His father fierce of treason false accused,
Her truth had staind with treason so vnkind;
Arise, and with like treason now maintain
By forged treason, or by open fight
Which two through treason and deceiptfull gin,
Or of himselfe to treason ill disposd
And loyall truth to treason doest incline;
Disloyall Treason, and hart-burning Hate,
Was neuer wight, that treason of him told;
Or did he fall by treason, or by fight?
The faithfull steele such treason no'uld endure,
Nought else, but treason, from the first this la[n]d did foyle.
Th'eternall markes of treason may at Stonheng vew.
Vnweeting of their wile and treason bad,
And bad, that none their ioyous treason should reueale.
Vile treason and fowle falshood hidden were,
And louely haulst from feare of treason free,
And that same Squire of treason to vpbraide.
For hatred, murther, treason, and despight,
Of treason, or some guilefull traine did weaue,
Perceiuing well the treason, which was ment:
And all that treason there intended did bewray.
And many brought to shame by treason treacherous.
By guilefull treason and by subtill slight
Then thou, that shall thy treason vnderstand,
Art thou he, traytor, that with treason vile,
To worke by wicked treason wayes doth find,
Great treason to him meant, his life to reaue.
How euer they through treason doe trespasse.
That haue with treason thralled vnto you
The secret treasons, which of late I know
But thou thy treasons fruit, I hope, shalt taste
That treasons could bewray, and foes conuince;
For to auenge, full many treasons vile
But for vyld treasons, and outrageous shame,
And all her traynes, and all her treasons forth did lay.
Ne yet entrap in treasons subtill traine.
doe gaine their treasons meed;
Breake in, and spoile the treasure there in gard:
And bearing with him treasure in close store,
Great store of treasure, therewith him to tempt;
To weete the treasure, which he did bewray,
With burden of great treasure, I thinke best
Your treasure here in some securitie,
Where late his treasure he entombed had,
And the hid treasures in her sacred tombe,
Ne priuie be vnto your treasures graue.
And treasures of true loue enlocked beene,
Vnkindnesse past, they gan of solace treat,
Whiles thus I heare you of your sorrowes treat.
Or bide him battell without further treat.
Where all that night they of their loues did treat,
To stay his hand, and of a truce to treat
Whereof I haue to treat here presently.
And would no lenger treat, but bad them sound.
To treat with her by way of enterdeale,
And often treat for pardon and remission
Whether this heauenly thing, whereof I treat,
That they mote treat of things abrode at leasure;
The coward Turpine, whereof now I treat;
And gan to treate of deeds of armes abrode,
Thus as they two of kindnesse treated long,
Thus when they long had treated to and fro,
Had no delight to treaten of his griefe;
Would him disarme, and treaten shamefully,
Yet first he cast by treatie, and by traynes,
Then she began a treatie to procure,
And with faire treatie pacifide their ire,
That with this present treatise doth agree,
And eke the Prince like treaty handeled,
And for these wrongs shall treble penaunce pay
Of treble good: good growes of euils priefe.
His treble, a straunge kinde of harmony;
That she conceiu'd; and trebling the dew time,
Trebly augmented was his furious mood
Them trebly breaded in a threefold lace,
Vnto the third, that his may so be trebly wext.
That hast with knightlesse guile and trecherous train
Made it selfe famous through false trechery,
Thinking to ouerthrow and downe him tred:
Ne scarse his feet on ground were seene to tred;
But once a man Fradubio, now a tree,
Wretched man, wretched tree; whose nature weake,
For though a tree I seeme, yet cold and heat me paines.
Say on Fradubio then, or man, or tree,
Now not a Lady, but a seeming tree;
When all this speech the liuing tree had spent,
Duessa placed is, and on a tree
Like to an Almond tree ymounted hye
That downe he tombled; as an aged tree,
For as the tree does fall, so lyes it euer low.
On cursed tree, of that vnspotted lam,
There grew a goodly tree him faire beside,
The tree of life, the crime of our first fathers fall.
Another like faire tree eke grew thereby,
That tree through one mans fault hath doen vs all to dy.
From that first tree forth flowd, as from a well,
As budding braunch rent from the natiue tree,
Of his fiers foe, him to a tree applies,
Was shot vp high, full of the stately tree,
No tree, whose braunches did not brauely spring;
Next thereunto did grow a goodly tree,
The warlike Elfe much wondred at this tree,
Of sleeping praise, were hong vpon a tree,
And languish as the leafe falne from the tree,
And eke enrooted deepe must be that Tree,
For though like withered tree, that wanteth iuyce,
Like as a withered tree through husbands toyle
And eke by that he saw on euery tree,
No tree, that is of count, in greenewood growes,
Saues Terpine from the gallow tree,
As ready for the gallow tree prepard:
So on a tree, before the Tyrants dore,
Flying from tree to tree, from wand to wand:
Flying from tree to tree, from wand to wand:
Hath pruned from the natiue tree, and cropped quight.
Both hand and foote vnto a tree was bound:
Till his returne vnto this tree he bond:
He lent against a tree, that backeward onset bard.
Had for his food late gathered from the tree,
He by the heeles him hung vpon a tree,
So left her, where she now is turnd to treen mould.
The wretched payre transform'd to treen mould;
Whose loftie trees yclad with sommers pride,
Much can they prayse the trees so straight and hy,
Where grew two goodly trees, that faire did spred
And trees did tremble. Th'Elfe therewith astownd,
Both loftie towres and highest trees hath rent,
And all about old stockes and stubs of trees,
That high trees ouerthrew, and rocks in peeces tore.
On gallow trees, in honour of his dearest Dame.
Trees, braunches, birds, and songs were framed fit,
The trees did bud, and earely blossomes bore,
And trees of bitter Gall, and Heben sad,
And the tall trees with leaues apparelled,
The painted flowres, the trees vpshooting hye,
With shady Laurell trees, thence to defend
Planted with mirtle trees and laurels greene,
And eke attonce the heauy trees they clime,
A gloomy groue of mirtle trees did rise,
But of the trees owne inclination made,
Through the tops of the high trees she did descry
For mossy trees, which couered all with shade
Against the stones and trees did rayle anew,
With diuers trees, enrang'd in euen rankes;
In which all trees of honour stately stood,
Did often tremble at his horrid vew,
My fearefull flesh did tremble at their strife,
And trees did tremble. Th'Elfe therewith astownd,
Whose tender locks do tremble euery one
And tremble like a leafe of Aspin greene,
